Washington DC Transit Oriented Development

Jonathan Manurung

September, 2023

What is Transit Oriented Development?

Transit-Oriented Development (TOD) describe by the United States Department of Transport as the dense, walkable, and mixed-use spaces near transit, intended to bring connectivity between transit services and the household nearby. TOD recommends increasing housing and amenity around transit station such as rail, subway, bus, etc. High density around TOD will promote efficiency in operating the transit system. TOD is also important for land value capitalization because its relation to rent price and property tax return. Interestingly, most transit systems in many major city are remarkably inefficient.

TOD analysis in Washington D.C, a city with an extensive public transportation network, examines whether residents are willing to pay a premium to live in TOD areas, reflecting the benefits of proximity to transit, reduced commuting costs and time to access their office or any other amenities.

Relating Washington D.C. Census Tracts and Metro Stations in space

To understand whether TOD areas are valued more than non-TOD areas, appropriate methodology is needed. Relating the census variables and metro stations in space is necessary to examine the relationship.

Data from American Community Survey (ACS) data from year 2009 and year 2019 are used as indicators, and linked spatially with the D.C.s Metro stations and lines, which are collected from Open Data DC. The metro subway in Washington DC has six lines and 98 stations across the broader Washington metropolitan area (see Figure 1.1).

To get better understanding on how TOD and related census characteristic have evolved over time, data from two points are used: 2009 vs 2019. This comparison will allow us to observe trends and changes, identify areas of growth or decline, and make relative comparisons. Census variables that linked to residents willingness to pay for TOD are, median rent price, median household income, percentage of public transit user, and percentage of non family households in the surrounding area.

Closeness is relative and instinctual to human beings. In TOD analysis, close is defined as area within a half mile (2,640 ft.) of a single transit station.

There are some techniques that can be applied in order to define which areas are TOD, and which areas are non-TOD, and creating a Buffers, is one of them. Polygon buffers with boundaries of 2,640 ft from metro stations are generated and overlaid, created an Unioned Buffer for the whole transit system (see Figure 1.2).

metro_stations_buffers <- 
  rbind(
    st_buffer(metro_stations_exp, 2640) %>%
      mutate(Legend = "Buffer") %>%
      select(Legend),
    st_union(st_buffer(metro_stations_exp, 2640)) %>%
      st_sf() %>%
      mutate(Legend = "Unioned Buffer"))

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data= st_union(allDC), fill = NA, colour = "black") +
  geom_sf(data=metro_stations_buffers, color ="red") +
  geom_sf(data=metro_stations_exp, show.legend = "point") +
  labs(title = "Unioned Buffer", subtitle = "Washington DC Metro Stations", caption = "Figure 2")+
  mapTheme()+
  theme(plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 8))

In order to select tracts that fall inside of the buffer, there are three different approaches used in this case, including: Intersection, Spatial Selection, and Select by Centroids (see Figure 1.3)

buffer <- filter(metro_stations_buffers, Legend=="Unioned Buffer")

clip <- 
  st_intersection(buffer, allDC) %>%
    select(geometry) %>%
    mutate(Selection_Type = "Clip")

selection <- 
  allDC[buffer,] %>%
    select(geometry) %>%
    mutate(Selection_Type = "Spatial Selection")

selectCentroids <-
  st_centroid(allDC)[buffer,] %>%
    st_drop_geometry() %>%
    left_join(select(allDC, GEOID)) %>%
    st_sf() %>%
    dplyr::select(geometry) %>%
    mutate(Selection_Type = "Select by Centroids")

intersections <- rbind(clip, selection, selectCentroids)

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data=intersections, fill = "#f0f9e8", color = "#0868ac") +
  geom_sf(data=metro_stations_exp, show.legend = "point", color = "black", size = 1) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c() +
  facet_wrap(~Selection_Type) +
  labs(title = "TOD Tracts Selection Approach", subtitle = "Washington DC Metro Stations", caption = "Figure 3")+
  mapTheme()+
  theme(
    strip.text.x = element_text(size = 10))

Select by Centroid is the most complicated and detailed approach, as it selects all the tract centroids that intersect the buffer area. It also capture a concise set of tracts without altering geometries, making it a more reliable option for TOD and non-TOD tract selection (see Figure 4)

allDCdat <-  
  rbind(
    st_centroid(allDC)[buffer, ] %>%
      st_drop_geometry() %>%
      left_join(allDC) %>%
      st_sf() %>%
      mutate(TOD = "TOD"),
    st_centroid(allDC)[buffer, op = st_disjoint] %>%
      st_drop_geometry() %>%
      left_join(allDC) %>%
      st_sf() %>%
      mutate(TOD = "Non-TOD")
  )

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data=allDCdat, aes(fill = TOD)) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("TOD" = "#f0f9e8", "Non-TOD" = "#0868ac")) +
  labs(title = "TOD an Non-TOD Census Tract", subtitle = "Washington DC Metro Stations", caption = "Figure 4")+
  mapTheme()

Four census variables that selected earlier as indicators, are plotted across time and space into multiple TOD indicator maps to visualize the comparison between TOD and non-TOD census tracts (see Figure 5)

TOD_tracts <- allDCdat %>%

The area within the red border in the maps indicate TOD census tracts. These visualizations indicate Median rent price in most of the census tract inside and outside the TOD generally increased during the 10 years period from 2009 to 2019. The increase also happened for both median household income and percentage of non-family household in Washington DC area during this period. Meanwhile we can see from the maps that the percentage people that use public transport to commute in TOD area remained stable (slightly declined) from 2009 to 2019, while non-TOD tracts recorded noticeable increases.

While the maps illustrate changes across all census tracts, grouped bar plot and table summarized key indicators for TOD and non-TOD census tracts in 2009 and 2019 (see Figure 6 and Table 1)

allDC.Summary <- 
  st_drop_geometry(allDCdat) %>%
    group_by(year, TOD) %>%
    summarize(Rent = mean(Medgrosrent, na.rm = T),
              Income = mean(Medhhinc, na.rm = T),
              Pct_Public_Transport_User = mean(pctpubtransuser, na.rm = T),
              Pct_Non_Family_Household = mean(pctnonfamhh, na.rm = T))

allDC.Summary %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -year, -TOD) %>%
  ggplot(aes(year, Value, fill = TOD)) +
    geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
    facet_wrap(~Variable, scales = "free", ncol=5) +
    scale_fill_manual(values = c("#f0f9e8", "#0868ac")) +
    labs(title = "Indicator differences across time and space", caption = "Figure 6") +
    plotTheme() + theme(legend.position="bottom", strip.text.x = element_text(size = 7))

allDC.Summary %>%
  unite(year.TOD, year, TOD, sep = ": ", remove = T) %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -year.TOD) %>%
  mutate(Value = round(Value, 2)) %>%
  spread(year.TOD, Value) %>%
  kable() %>%
    kable_styling() %>%
    footnote(general_title = "\n",
             general = "Table 1")

The grouped bar plots and table make it easier to observe that rent prices, median household income, and percent of non-family household in both TOD and non-TOD census tracts were increasing during the period of 2009 to 2019. They also capture the decrease of percent of public transportation user in both TOD and non-TOD census tracts

Population and rent are the strongest census characteristics that indicate the amount of resident that willing to pay in a TOD area. TOD areas near Metro stations in Northwest and Northeast D.C. have the largest populations, while those in the Southwest have the smallest. In terms of median rent TOD areas near Metro stations in Northwest D.C. have the highest median rent, while those in the Northeast have the lowest as seen in this following interactive graduated symbol map.

tmap_mode("view")

metro_stations$station_id <- seq_len(nrow(metro_stations))
TOD_tracts <- st_intersection(allDC, metro_stations)

# Population
TOD_agg_pop <- TOD_tracts %>%
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>%       
  group_by(station_id, year) %>%  
  summarise(total_population = sum(TotalPop, na.rm = TRUE))

stations_2009 <- metro_stations %>%
  left_join(TOD_agg_pop %>% filter(year == 2009), by = "station_id")

Pop_Grad_Map_2009 <-
  tm_shape(stations_2009) +
  tm_bubbles(col = "red",
             size = "total_population",
             border.col = "black",
             border.lwd = 1,
             scale = 2,
             title.size = "Population 2009")

stations_2019 <- metro_stations %>%
  left_join(TOD_agg_pop %>% filter(year == 2019), by = "station_id")


Pop_Grad_Map_2019 <-
  tm_shape(stations_2019) +
  tm_bubbles(col = "blue",
             size = "total_population",
             border.col = "black",
             border.lwd = 1,
             scale = 2,
             title.size = "Population 2019")

# Rent
TOD_agg_rent <- TOD_tracts %>%
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>%      
  group_by(station_id, year) %>%  
  summarise(median_rent = sum(Medhhinc, na.rm = TRUE))

stations_2009 <- metro_stations %>%
  left_join(TOD_agg_rent %>% filter(year == 2009), by = "station_id")

Rent_Grad_Map_2009 <-
  tm_shape(stations_2009) +
  tm_bubbles(col = "red",
             size = "median_rent",
             border.col = "black",
             border.lwd = 1,
             scale = 2,
             title.size = "Rent 2009")

stations_2019 <- metro_stations %>%
  left_join(TOD_agg_rent %>% filter(year == 2019), by = "station_id")


Rent_Grad_Map_2019 <-
  tm_shape(stations_2019) +
  tm_bubbles(col = "blue",
             size = "median_rent",
             border.col = "black",
             border.lwd = 1,
             scale = 2,
             title.size = "Rent 2019")

tmap_arrange(Pop_Grad_Map_2009, Pop_Grad_Map_2019, Rent_Grad_Map_2009, Rent_Grad_Map_2019, ncol = 2, nrow = 2)

Are Washington D.C.s Residents Willing to Pay More for TOD?

There is insufficient evidence to draw firm conclusions regarding whether residents are willing to pay more for TOD areas. It is critical to understand how omitted variables affect the relevant spatial process and ultimately, the results of an analysis. The increase of median rent price in the area from 2009 to 2019 may appear to reflect residents willingness to pay more for TOD areas. However, when considered alongside increasing household incomes, such increases can also be seen as a natural outcome, reflecting general price growth and inflation.

Declining percentage of public transport user both in TOD and non-TOD area explains that residents are not relying on public transport for commuting. Giving the assumption that accessibility to public transport may not something that the residents are looking for when they decided to live in TOD area. It could be that they pay more for other amenities in neighborhoods that happen to also be transit-rich.

Function between mean rent and distance to subway stations does not indicate that properties closest to the subway are more expensive than the further properties (see Figure 7)

Further study is necessary to explore the determinants of residential choice in TOD areas, including the role of transit accessibility, housing costs, and demographic factors.

TOD_buffers <-
  multipleRingBuffer(st_union(metro_stations),23760,2640)

halfmile_buf <- 
  ggplot()+
  geom_sf(data= st_union(allDC), fill = NA, colour = "black") +
  geom_sf(data = metro_stations, show.legend = "point" )+
  geom_sf(data = TOD_buffers, fill =NA, colors ="black")+
  labs(title = "D.C.'s Metro Station Half Mile Buffers")+
  mapTheme()+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 12))


tracts_buffered <- st_join(allDC, TOD_buffers, join = st_intersects)

tracts_distance <-
  ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = tracts_buffered, aes(fill = q5(distance))) +
  geom_sf(data = metro_stations, color = "red", size = 1) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = palette5,
                    labels = qBr(tracts_buffered, "distance"),
                    name = "Distance\n(miles)") +
  labs(title = "Distance to Metro Station") +
  mapTheme()+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 12))

rent_by_distance <- tracts_buffered %>%
  mutate(distance_miles = distance / 5280) %>%
  group_by(year, distance_miles) %>%
  summarise(mean_rent = mean(Medgrosrent, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  filter(!all(is.nan(mean_rent))) %>%
  ungroup()%>%
  group_by(distance_miles) %>%
  filter(all(!is.nan(mean_rent))) %>%  # keep only distances where both years have data
  ungroup()

rent_dist_line <-
  ggplot() +
  geom_line(data = rent_by_distance, aes(x = distance_miles, y = mean_rent, color = factor(year)), size = 2) +
  labs(
    x = "Distance to Subway Station (Miles)",
    y = "Mean Rent",
    color = "Year",
    title = "Mean Rent as a Function of Distance to Subway Stations (2009 vs 2019)"
  ) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("2009" = "#f0f9e8", "2019" = "#0868ac")) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(size = 12)
  )


grid.arrange(halfmile_buf, tracts_distance,rent_dist_line, ncol = 2,
bottom = textGrob("Figure 7", gp = gpar(fontsize = 12)))
